description: From in- +‎ hold. Compare Old English onhealdan (“to hold, keep, maintain”). More at in, hold.

verbs.description: inhold (third-person singular simple present inholds, present participle inholding, simple past inheld, past participle inheld or (obsolete) inholden)

examples: Sound implicates these obscure tethers, which connect sound to noise, thereby giving sound its sense. The implicated difference inholds an obscure reserve of sense.

entries.meaning: To possess inherently, contain in oneself.
examples: If to the living were my muse addressed, Or did my mind her own spirit still inhold
